@AndiBasha3 @Bongo_King1 Nodes can set their own op_return limit. They could do this both before and after v30.

It’s a relay policy that each node has control over for themselves.

@AndiBasha3 @Bongo_King1 That’s what the block size limit is for.

@AndiBasha3 @Bongo_King1 This fork doesn’t materially affect how much non-monetary data can be put into a block, nor does it substantially increase the cost of adding it.

Monetary use is currently low, which means low fees and low costs of spam.

@AndiBasha3 @Bongo_King1 All else being equal, I’d like to see less non-monetary data in bitcoin. If someone proposes a way to materially reduce it with few trade-offs, I’d be happy to see it.

But no, I’m not concerned by it.

@Puncher522 @Bongo_King1 One of the nice parts about bitcoin is that people can test their feelings in the market whenever they want.

Every fork is a market check.

@mdubore @Bongo_King1 This fork doesn’t materially fix any taproot issues, though.

And I’m not throwing stones. I’m answering questions or responding to people who seem misinformed about what this fork can or cannot do and how we got here.

@mdubore @Bongo_King1 Spammers can just break it into chunks and still stick it in the witness. For minimal additional cost.

@R_Relaxation @Bongo_King1 Every node can change their op return limit. You can set it to what you want.

They just changed the defaults for their implementation. You can run it and change them back, or run a different implementation with different defaults. This was always the case.

@RayThisLife02 What makes you think this affects the company in any way?

It’s a private equity business that seeks to hold bitcoin as sound money.

@DBonatOliv @RayThisLife02 Current rules are 2023 rules, in terms of consensus.

And this fork proposal as currently constructed doesn’t materially reduce block space for spam, nor does it materially increase the cost of adding it.

@RayThisLife02 Nothing is in it for me or the company, lol.

I didn’t even initiate anything about it. I was asked about it in a podcast once, then got several dozen fork proponents responding, showing common signs people have when in an echo chamber. So I invited them to check their context.

@DBonatOliv @RayThisLife02 Standardness rules are set at the node level. Users can set them to what they want, including to 2023 defaults.

Regarding spam, you’re the one that brought up space reduction. But there is no material space reduction for spam in this fork where it’s cheapest (the witness).

